Calvin Austin came back to Earth after his big Week 1 with only 3.2 PPR points in Week 2. He's a volatile flex play with a good matchup this week. Austin has seen one red zone target this season. He has a 13.8% target share, a 51.9% air-yard share, 1.56 yards per route run (46 receiving yards per game), and a 17.8% first-read share. The Patriots have allowed the 11th-most PPR points per target to perimeter wide receivers (Austin 50.8% on the perimeter).

Tyquan Thonton is flex viable. Last week, he had a 17.2% target share with a 60.9% air-yard share (34.0 aDOT), 59 receiving yards (2.11 yards per route run), and a 25% first-read share (led the team). He's operating as Patrick Mahomes' deep threat, which isn't a bad role to have this week. The Giants have allowed the sixth-most deep passing yards per game and are tied for the 12th-highest deep ball completion rate (adjusted). The Giants also have utilized single-high at the seventh-highest rate (60.6%). Against single high, Thornton leads the team with 2.57 yards per route run and is second with a 24% first-read share. He could easily take a deep target to the house again this week. The Giants have allowed the 11th-most PPR points per target to perimeter wide receivers.

DeAndre Hopkins has run incredibly hot with his minimal usage in a Ravens jersey. Through two games, Hopkins has had a 32.7% route share with an 8.3% target share and a 5.9% first-read share. He has averaged only two targets per game, but 49.5 receiving yards, and has two scores. This is incredibly flukey, and you still can't put Hopkins into a fantasy lineup unless his usage changes.

Xavier Legette is droppable. Through two games, he has only a 13.3% target share with 0.10 yards per route run and a 20% first-read share. He wasn't efficient with the volume he received last year, and that hasn't changed in 2025. The Panthers need Jalin Coker to return soon.

Luther Burden is borderline droppable at this point. He ran only four routes in Week 2. Could this change in the upcoming weeks? Yep. It's easily possible, but Caleb Williams currently is only supporting one fantasy asset in this offense. Until his play improves, asking him to support the third or fourth speculative option in the passing attack is too much.

Jake Ferguson is the TE7 in fantasy, absorbing a 20.9% target share and 25.4% first-read share while producing 1.46 yards per route run and 50.5 receiving yards per game. He'll face a pass defense that has utilized the fifth-highest rate of two high (62.3%). Against two high, Ferguson has seen his target share increase to 23.8% with 2.16 yards per route run and a 33.3% first-read share. He should be busy in Week 3 as Dak Prescott's second option in the passing attack. Chicago is 18th in fantasy points per game allowed to tight ends.

Juwan Johnson is the TE2 in fantasy points per game while absorbing a massive workload in the Saints' offense. He has a 25% target share, 1.71 yards per route run (62.5 receiving yards per game), and a 31.5% first-read share. Johnson leads the team with three red zone targets. It has been awesome to see. Seattle has the second-highest two-high rate in the NFL (69.2%). Against two high, Johnson has been the second option in the passing game with a 20% target share and 25% first-read share (both second on the team behind only Chris Olave). Johnson should have another strong game this week against a Seattle defense that has allowed the fourth-most fantasy points per game and 11th-most receiving yards to tight ends.

Zach Ertz is the TE3 in fantasy points per game. He has a 16.7% target share with 1.34 yards per route run and a 20.9% first-read share. He has spiked touchdowns in both games this season. Las Vegas utilizes zone coverage at the highest rate in the NFL (92.9%). Against zone, Ertz has seen his target share increase to 17.4% with 1.68 yards per route run and a 24% first-read share. The Raiders have allowed the fifth-most yards per reception to tight ends. Ertz is a locked-in TE1.

T.J. Hockenson has gotten off to a quiet start as the TE43 in fantasy points per game. He has a 17.1% target share (3.5 targets per game) with 13.5 receiving yards per game (0.66 yards per route run) and an 18.2% first-read share. The market share metrics have been fine, but with Minnesota moving to a more run-heavy approach, the volume just hasn't been there. You're probably starting Hockenson this week because of the state of the tight end position, but I can't tell you to feel great about it. The matchup is at least in his favor. The Bengals have allowed the 14th-highest yards per reception and the tenth-most receiving yards to tight ends.

I was down on Kyle Pitts last week, but I'm back in with Pitts this week as a strong tight end play. I worry about how much Atlanta will pass, but the bar to clear for a tight end to be a TE1 weekly isn't a high one. Pitts is the TE13 in fantasy points per game seeing a 20.6% target share with 1.57 yards per route run and a 19.6% first-read share. This coverage shell matchup is perfect for him to succeed. Carolina has utilized single high with 56.5% of their defensive snaps. Against single high, Pitts has seen his target share balloon to 28.6% with 1.91 yards per route run and a 25% first-read share. Carolina has allowed the sixth-most yards per reception and the third-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Harold Fannin Jr. could post another nice stat line this week. He's the TE9 in fantasy points per game, drawing a 15.1% target share (58.6% route share) with 55.5 receiving yards per game (1.91 yards per route run) and a 20.8% first-read share (second on the team). Fannin Jr. has one red zone target. The Packers have allowed the fifth-most fantasy points per game, the 11th-highest yards per reception, and the fifth-most receiving yards to tight ends. He could be Joe Flacco's go-to receiver this week.

David Njoku could finally have a TE1 week against the Packers. Njoku is the TE20 in fantasy points per game, seeing a 10.8% target share with a 75.8% route share. He has averaged only 38.5 receiving yards (1.03 yards per route run) with an 11.3% first-read share. These numbers aren't amazing, but the matchup is juicy. The Packers have allowed the fifth-most fantasy points per game, the 11th-highest yards per reception, and the fifth-most receiving yards to tight ends.

After seeing only a 55.8% route share in Week 1, Dalton Kincaid looked like he could be in store for an expanded role in Week 2, but the gamescript crushed him. The Bills smothered the Jets in a blowout, and their starters' usage was muddied as they benched them in the second half. In the first half, Kincaid had a 70% route share, so we could see that the playing time threshold comes to fruition in Week 3 if Miami can keep this game competitive. Overall, Kincaid has a 21% target per route run rate, 1.81 yards per route run, and a 13.6% first-read share. He is also tied for the team lead in red zone targets (two). Kincaid and Khalill Shakir could be the receiving threats that Josh Allen leans on this week. The Dolphins have allowed the tenth-highest yards per reception and the 12th-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Hunter Henry is the TE22 in fantasy points per game. He has a 66.3% route share, a 15.9% target share, 1.36 yards per route run (37.5 receiving yards per game), and a 17.6% first-read share. He's a decent tight end streaming option again this week. The Steelers have allowed the seventh-most yards per reception and the 12th-most fantasy points per game to tight ends. Drake Maye is spreading the targets around, so Henry is probably a little more volatile than he might seem on paper. After eight targets in Week 1, he had only three targets in Week 2.

Through two games, Mark Andrews has a total of four targets, seven receiving yards, and zero touchdowns. This is despite him leading the team with two red zone targets, having a 70.9% route share. He has had only an 11.8% first-read share. That first-read share did climb to 15.8% in Week 2, so I do think that Andrews will have better days coming. We'll see if that is in Week 2, but I don't have high hopes. The Lions rank 16th in yards per reception allowed to tight ends and have also given up the 11th-fewest fantasy points per game to the position.

Brenton Strange is the TE21 in fantasy points per game. He has a 64.9% route share, a 12.3% target share, 1.52 yards per route run (38 receiving yards per game, and a 13.6% first-read share. He's not on the tight end streaming radar this week. Houston has allowed the second-fewest yards per reception and the third-fewest fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Chig Okonkwo is the TE22 in fantasy points per game. He has a 73.3% route share, a 16.4% target share, 0.98 yards per route run, and a 14.6% first-read share. None of those stats make him streamer-worthy this week. The Colts have allowed the sixth-fewest fantasy points per game and yards per reception to tight ends.

After missing Week 2, Dallas Goedert will be back in the lineup this week. In Week 1, Goedert was the TE10 as he saw a 30.4% target share and 30% first-read share producing 44 receiving yards (1.57 yards per route run). I don't see Goedert gobbling up a 30% target share in Week 3, but he could easily flirt with TE1 numbers. Last year, the Rams allowed the third-highest yards per reception, the sixth-most receiving yards, and the fourth-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

Through two games, Jonnu Smith has a 52.1% route share, a 15.4% target share (-1.2 aDOT), 21 receiving yards per game (1.11 yards per route run), one red zone target, and a 17.8% first-read share. If you're struggling for a tight end to play this week, Smith is on the LOW end of the tight end streaming radar. The Patriots have allowed the seventh-most receiving yards and the third-most yards per reception to tight ends.

Ja'Tavion Sanders is a low-end streaming tight end option this week. It's simply a volume play if you're desperate. Last week, Sanders had a 66.1% route share with a 16.4% target share, 1.38 yards per route run (54 receiving yards), and a 24.2% first-read share. The Falcons have defended only six tight end targets this season, allowing one reception and 12 scoreless receiving yards. Last year, Atlanta allowed the 12th-most fantasy points per game and the seventh-most yards per reception to tight ends. Sanders could flirt with TE1 production this week. He was the TE6 in fantasy last week.

Cade Otton is on the streaming tight end radar this week. If Mike Evans gets shadowed by Sauce Gardner, Otton could see a bump in usage. Otton has an 8.6% target share, only 0.40 yards per route run (12.5 receiving yards per game), and an 8.9% first-read share. The Jets have allowed the 13th-most receiving yards and the ninth-most fantasy points per game to tight ends.

If you're desperate for a tight end streaming option, Pat Freiermuth is on the fringe of this discussion for Week 3. Freiermuth has had a 50.7% route share, a 10.8% target share, 29.5 receiving yards per game (1.59 yards per route run, an 11.1% first-read share, and a red zone target. He has been the more traditional tight end, while Jonnu Smith has been the designed target option. The Patriots have allowed the seventh-most receiving yards and the third-most yards per reception to tight ends.

Colston Loveland remains unstartable in fantasy football. In Week 2, he still only played a part-time role with a 47.5% route share and 3% target share. Until he supplants Cole Kmet as the every-down tight end, he has to remain on the bench.

Well, so much for the Joke role in Sean Payton's offense. Evan Engram still isn't a full-time player in the Denver offense. In Week 2, he had a 43.8% route share and only a 6.7% target share. He's droppable at this point. It's wild that Denver made the move to acquire his services this season and won't put him out on the field.

Nick Bosa was excellent in Week 2, racking up three solos, six assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He is up to nine solos, six assists, two sacks, and four tackles for loss on the season, keeping him in the elite DL conversation for a plus Week 3 matychup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Myles Garrett was excellent in Week 2, racking up two solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and two tackles for loss.  Now up to 3.5 sacks on the season, Garrett is a top-three option for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Green Bay Packers.

Trey Hendrickson was at it again in Week 2, notching two solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Hendrickson has one sack in back-to-back games, but continues to offer IDP managers very little when he's not getting sacks. But when he can lead the league in sacks, who cares? Start Trey with confidence as a top-10 option for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Minnesota Vikings.

Carl Granderson was excellent in Week 2, tallying five solos, two assists, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. Granderson has started the season on fire and looks poised to match or surpass the 8.5 sacks he recorded in 2023. Tap Granderson as a DL2 option as long as he is cooking.

Burns continues to produce, most recently reeling off three solos, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Burns should be roasted in all competitive leagues, regardless of provider and positional designation. Treat Burns as a DL1/LB2 option for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs on Sunday night.

DeForest Buckner went off in Week 1, tallying five solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. The production was more in line with expectations than his quiet opener, in which he managed just three assists. Buckner is one of the more active defensive tackles in the solo department, making him one of the safest options at his position. Tap Buckner as a DL2 option for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Travon Walker was excellent in Week 3, tallying three solos, two assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. Walker is a top-15 option for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against a leaky Houston Texans offensive line. Start him everywhere.

Kobie Turner showed up in Week 2, notching three solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss against the Tennessee Titans. He had eight sacks just last season and should remain in the DT1/DL3 for Week 3 and beyond.

Young went off against the Titans, reeling off four solos, one assist, two sacks, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Now up to three sacks on the season, Young looks set for a career year. The matchup will not be as good this week against Jalen Hurts and the Eagles, but he will stack three plus matchups in the four following games. Add and start Young as a DL2 option who becomes an elite DL2 play in plus matchups.

Josh Sweat was excellent in Week 2, racking up three solos, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. Sweat is a solid DL3 option and should be treated as such for a plus matchup against a banged up San Francisco 49ers offense. Make the add where needed.

Kayvon was excellent in Week 2, racking up four solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Thibodeaux played 70 percent of the snaps for the second week in a row and saw plenty of time with both Brian Burns and Abdul Carter (54.1 percent). There is no reason for a proven DL2 to be on the wire in any format when they are playing 70 percent of the snaps. Add and start Kayvon everywhere for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Dallas Turner was a workhorse with Andrew Van Ginkel sidelined, playing a whopping 91 percent of the snaps and responding with three solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Turner will likely go back to a receiving role when AVG returns from concussion protocol, but his performance this past weekend should have earned him a larger role going forward, regardless. Make the stash where roster size permits.

Bosa was at it again in Week 2, notching one solo tackle, one assist, one sack, one tackle for loss, and two forced fumbles. Bosa now has three forced fumbles in three games and should be treated seriously as a DL3/4 option as long as he is cooking. His upside is capped due to the rotation on the edge, but he played more snaps than Greg Rosseau (55 percent to 53 percent) and should continue to figure prominently in the rotation as long as he is making an impact on the field.

Made his presence felt in Week 2, tallying two solos, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. Milton is an east DT1 play but is creating enough havoc to trust as a DL3 option, especially when given plus matchups. Tap him as a DL3/4 play for a neutral Week 3 matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Armstrong was at it again in Week 2, reeling off four solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He is riding a two game sack streak to start the season (two total), and has four solos in both, something that could push him into DL2 conversation if he can keep up the activity when he's not getting sacks. For now, continue to treat him as a DL3 with DL2 upside. Make the add in all competitive leagues.

Wyatt was at it again in Week 2, racking up two solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He has a sack in back-to-back games and is back in the fant
asy mix now that he's a starter again. Add him as a DT2 option with DT1 upside where needed.

Calais continues to make an impact, most recently racking up four solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss. He has had a strong start to the season and can now be counted as a strong flex option. He's back in the DT1 conversation as long as he is hot and can be tapped as a DL3/4 type where needed. Make the add in competitive leagues.

Mykel Williams had a better showing in Week 2, racking up four solos, one assist, and two tackles for loss. He has yet to record his first sack, but he is creating pressures and making timely stops. Mykel should start his sack ledger sooner rather than later, perhaps even as soon as this week, thanks to a plus matchup against the Arizona Cardinals. Start him as a DL3 option where needed.

James Pearce played just 36 percent of the snaps in Week 2, recording two assists and 0.5 sacks. Pearce is going to be starting on the edge sooner or later, but expectations need to continue to be tempered for the Falcons' edge duo. Pearce should be rostered in 16+ team leagues but should be left on wires elsewhere, at least for now.

Murphy has had a strong start to the season, most recently recording two solos, three assists, 1.5 sacks, and one tackle for loss. His inspired IDP production has put him on the DT1 radar, but for now, slide him in as an elite DT2. He is a DL4 for those not in DT leagues.

We had a Jack Sawyer sighting in Week 2. He played just 40 percent of the snaps but still managed four solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. His strong play should have earned him a more consistent role going forward, putting the rookie on deep league radars. Sawyer becomes a deep league start with Alex Highsmith (ankle) projected to be sidelined for multiple weeks. He will split time with Nate Herbig, but has shown enough to warrant a flex or DL3 start if needed. Start him where needed for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Cleveland Browns.

Jarran Reed showed up in Week 2, tallying three solos, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Reed is one of the safer DT options due to his tackle count, but remains better served as DT2 as opposed to a DT1.

Roquan went bonkers in Week 2, tallying eight solos, seven assists, two tackles for loss, one fumble recovery, and one touchdown. He is proving why he was one of the first IDP names off the board in drafts this offseason and will look to keep the good times rolling against Detroit on Monday night. Tap Smith as a top-three option for the plus matchup.

Foye was excellent in Week 2, tallying three solos, four assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Foye remains an LB1 option but is no longer the consensus top play he once was. Still, he is one of the most consistent options at the position and should thrive against a struggling Houston Texans team in Week 3.

Edge was excellent again in Week 2, racking up seven solos, three assists, and 0.5 sacks. He has 15 solos in two contests, putting him in the LB1 mix for a tasty Week 3 matchup against the Cleveland Browns. Start him with confidence everywhere.

Fred Warner went off in Week 2, tallying seven solos, four assists, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, one fumble recovery, and one pass defended. Warner looks like a top-three option again this week with Arizona on tap, so fantasy managers should start him with confidence.

Ernest Jones was excellent in Week 2, tallying eight solos and two assists. Jones is one of the top options at the position, and that will be no different in Week 3. Start him as a top-10 play for a plus Week 3 matchup against the New Orleans Saints.

Jordyn Brooks was excellent in Week 2, racking up four solos, four assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Brooks has started the season hot and can be counted as a top-15 option until he cools down. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Sherwood was solid in Week 2, racking up six oslos, seven assists, and two tackles for loss. The solo count was low in Week 1, so it was good to see him stack the tackles against Buffalo. Tap him as a top-15 option for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Tampa Bay Buccaneers.

Landman was excellent in Week 2, reeling off four solos, four assists, and one fumble recovery. Landman has cemented himself as an LB2 option and should be treated as such for what should be a busy day at the office against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Jack Campbell was solid in Week 2, tallying four solos and four assists. Campbell had five slos and five assists in Week 1 and can be counted as a strong LB2 option for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Baltimore Ravens.

Okereke stayed hot in Week 2, tallying four solos, six assists, and one pass defended. Okerke is a strong LB2 option with top-15 upside for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Tyrel Dodson was excellent in Week 2, tallying six solos and three asists. He continues to dominate snaps at middle linebacker alongside Jordyn Brooks and should be treated as a LB2/3 option going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Buffalo Bills.

Demario Davis continues to turn back the clock for IDP managers, tallying five solos, six assists, and one fumble recovery in Week 2. He needs to be taken seriously as an LB2 option as long as he is cooking and should be treated as one for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Seattle Seahawks. Add Davis wherever available.

Spillane flashed in Week 2, notching three solos, one sack, and one pass defended. Managing just three solos after failing to top that mark in the opener raises the concern level here, as Spillane is not producing anywhere near the level expected for IDP managers, and it may be time to start thinking about leaving him on benches. He should not be dropped under any circumstances, but until he proves he can produce in this scheme at something above an LB3 level, there is no reason to plug him into lineups based on name equity alone. He is playing nearly every snap, so the good games shouldn't be too far off, but unless you play in a three LB league with multiple flex spots, he is someone to keep stashed and benched until he starts producing. Look elsewhere for Week 3.

Kenneth Murray looked good again in Week 2, tallying five solos, two assists, and two tackles for loss. Murray is an easy LB2 play for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Chicago Bears. If Murray is available in your league, add him immediately; he has LB1 upside.

Winters was excellent in Week 2, racking up six solos and two assists. Winters has made a name for himself through the first two weeks of the season and has positioned himself as an LB2 option for IDP purposes. Start him with confidence for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Arizona Cardinals.

Jihaad Campbell showed up in Week 2, tallying five solos and two assists. He looks like he is starting to get it going, but should still be counted as more of an LB3 than an LB2 for Week 3. Look elsewhere for Week 3 if you are seeking an LB2 option.

Payton Wilson showed up in a big way in Week 2, racking up eight solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. He will be inconsistent, making him more of a flex option during the non byes, but has the upside to plug in as an LB3 when needed. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Pace was excellent on Sunday night, reeling off seven solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Pace was quiet in Week 1, so it is nice to see him sniff his upside in Week 2. Pace remains more LB3 than LB2 for now, but has LB2 upside for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Cincinnati Bengals.

Bush showed up again in Week 2, tallying four solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Bush is playing at a high level for IDP managers and can be counted as an LB2 option until he slows down.

Sanborn dominated snaps beside Kenneth Murray in Week 2, pushing both Damone Clark and Marist Liufau to drop territory. Sanborn racked up a solid four solos and four assists against the New York Giants and should continue to provide LB3 numbers for fantasy managers. He has LB2 upside and could sit in that realm for an extended period, but he will need to show that he can produce in Dallas before we can start trusting him as a top-25 option outside of the byes. Add and start Sanborn where needed.

Devin Lloyd showed up in Week 2, racking up two solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Lloyd has had a disappointing IDP start to the season, playing just 34 percent of the snaps in Week 1 and struggling to produce outside of the pick in Week 2 despite 70 percent of the snaps. He is talented enough to keep as a bench stash, but he is not someone you want plugged into lineups outside of 16+ team leagues. Leave him on benches for Week 3 despite the plus matchup against the Houston Texans.

Dorian Williams played 64 percent of the snaps in Week 3 due to Matt Milano picking up an injury. With the Bills playing on a short week, Williams could get the start. Make the speculative add where possible.

Rashan Gary showed up again in Week 2, reeling off two solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Gary is up to 2.5 sacks on the season and should continue the march to new career highs thanks to all the attention Micah Parsons demands on the other side. Tap Gary as an easy DL2 option for Week 3.

Chubb was excellent in Week 2, racking up three solos, two assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Chubb has a sack in each of the first two games of the season and is firmly on the DL2 radar for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Buffalo Bills on Thursday night. Add and start Chubb where possible.

Tykee has been excellent to start the season, following up his seven solo, four assist Week 1 with four solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss against the Houston Texans on Monday Night Football. Tykee is pushing to be included in the DB2 conversation and will get there if he can keep stacking strong production. Start Tykee everywhere for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the New York Jets.

Moehrig was at it again in Week 2, ripping off seven solos and two assists. He has now put up two DB1 level performances in a row after tallying seven solos and four assists in Week 1 and is firmly in the DB2 mix for Week 3. Moehrig has a plus matchup on tap against Atlanta and should be started universally.

Brisker was excellent in Week 2, tallying seven solos and two assists. He is going to be inconsistent in the nickel role for the Bears but we all know he has elite tackle upside (even if it came at a different position). Tap Jaquan as a CB1 in CB leagues or a DB3 with DB1 upside in DB leagues.

Talanoa was excellent in Week 2, tallying five solos and five assists. He was even better in Week 1 with seven solos, four assists, and one forced fumble, and should continue to be taken seriously as a rejuvenated DB1 option. Start him everywhere for what should be a busy afternoon against the Los Angeles Chargers. 5-5, 7-4 ff Week 1

Kam Curl was excellent in Week 3, racking up five solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. Putting together a performance like this on the heels of an eight solo, two assist Week 1 puts Curl back in the DB1 mix going forward. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Philadelphia Eagles.

Chinn showed up in Week 2, racking up six solos and one tackle for loss. His production this week was more in line with expectations, keeping him in the DB1 mix for Week 3. The revenge game narrative is alive and well, so expect Chinn to be flying around the field against Washington like we are accustomed to.

Minkah had a solid week at the office in Week 2, racking up four solos and four assists. The veteran safety has 10 solos and seven assists through two contests, making him a DB1 option for Week 3. Start him with confidence everywhere.

Paulson Adebo proved he's going to continue to produce for IDP managers regardless of what uniform he is wearing, racking up 11 solos, two assists, and one pass defended. He now has 17 solos through two contests and is firmly in the DB2 mix for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Kansas City Chiefs.

Amani Hooker continues his strong play for the Titans, most recently notching five solos, three assists, one sack, and one tackle for loss against the Los Angeles Rams. Hooker has worked his way into the top-end DB2 conversation and should be starting in competitive leagues. Tap him as a top-25 option for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Indianapolis Colts.

Jalen Thompson continues to be a steady IDP force, tallying six solos and four assists in Week 2. He was solid in Week 1 with four solos, four assists, and one pass defended, and is a DB2 option for Week 3 and beyond. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the San Francisco 49ers.

3-1 one interception, and one pass defended. Bynum now has a pick in back-to-back games to open the season, but has mustered just four total solos in two weeks. Treat him as more DB3 than DB2 for Week 3 despite the excellent matchup against the Tennessee Titans.

Cooper DeJean showed up in Week 2, racking up six solos and two assists. He was solid in Week 1 with three solos, two assists, and one pass defended and should continue to produce in the nickel role for the Eagles. Tap him as an easy CB1 option in CB leagues or a DB3/4 in DB leagues. Start him where possible for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Los Angeles Rams.

Dax Hill shone in Week 2, racking up nine solos, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Hill is proving to be a valuable IDP play in the nickel role and has worked his way into the DB2 conversation with his strong start (five solos, four assists in Week 1). Start him everywhere for Week 2.

Wilson showed up in Week 2, racking up three solos, three assists, one interception, and one pass defended. Donovan has just three solos total in two games, making him a waiver wire or bench play for now. He has shown he can produce at a DB1 level in prior seasons, but has settled into more of a DB3/4 r
ole. He is not much of an option outside of the byes, especially with the explosion of valuable nickels in IDP. Look elsewhere for your Week 3 DB3 despite the plus matchup against the Chicago Bears.

Jourdan was excellent in Week 2, racking up five solos, three assists, two tackles for loss, and one pass defended. Lewis has been elite to start the season and should be counted as a potential DB2 option as long as he is cooking. Treat him as a CB1/DB3 where possible, but tap him as a DB2 if you find yourself in a bind. Start Lewis with confidence for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the struggling Houston Texans.

Bishop showed up in Week 2, reeling off four solos, one assist, one sack, and one tackle for loss. Cole has four solos in back-to-back games and makes for a solid DB3 option. He should work his way into the DB2 mix eventually, but IDP managers should be patient. Add and start Bishop as a strong DB3 option for Week 3, thanks to a plus matchup against the Miami Dolphins.

Chuck Clark has worked his way into the DB2 mix following back-to-back outings with six solos and two assists (he also had a tackle for loss in Week 1). He will likely settle in as a DB3 when all is said and done, but in IDP, we roll with the hot hand where possible. Tap him as a DB2 option for a plus Week 3 matchup against the New England Patriots.

Jalen Ramsey was excellent in Week 2, tallying four solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. Ramsey has been all over the field for the Steelers and should continue to provide solid production for IDP managers. Tap him as a DB2/3 option for Week 3.

Dru Hill went off in Week 2, reeling off eight solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and two passes defended. Dru is on the CB1 radar and also makes for a strong DB3/4 option for Week 4. Add and start Phillips where needed.

Murray went off in Week 2, tallying six solos, one assist, one interception, and one pass defended. Murray is a solid flex/flex 2 option, but is not yet in the DB3 mix outside of 16+ team leagues. Roster him where needed, but keep him benched for Week 3, despite the plus matchup against the Houston Texans. Look elsewhere for your Week 3 DB3.

Geno Stone was excellent in Week 2, tallying seven solos and two assists. Stone didn't do much in Week 1, so he remains a DB3 option as opposed to a DB2. Stone has flashed massive upside in the past, but has never quite come close to matching his production with the Ravens. He should provide some spike weeks, but don't expect DB1 numbers on a consistent basis.

Billy Bowman has been making plays for the Atlanta Falcons, most recently recording two solos, two assists, one interception, and two passes defended. He has yet to stack the solos(just two in each contest), but has been contributing in the peripherals and will be working on his tackle angles week in and week out. Tap Bowman as a DB4/flex2 where needed. Deep leaguers should roster Bowman where possible.

Tarheeb was excellent in Week 2, tallying seven solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended. Still has been flying around the field in the nickel role and only projects to get better. Still is an option in leagues of all sizes, but those in deeper formats will want to pay special attention after the waivers were likely picked bare after Week 1. Start Tarheeb as a strong DB3 option for a plus matchup against the Denver Broncos.

Wiggins has put himself on the DB3 radar with another strong outing, recording two solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, and three passes defended. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Detroit Lions on Monday Night Football.

Mukuba continues to start over Sydney Brown and is rewarding IDP managers, most recently tallying five solos, one assist, 0.5 sacks, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. He was quiet in Week 1, and we should expect some peaks and valleys, so treat him as more of a DB3 than a DB2 for Week 3. Add and start Mukuba where needed.
Dugger played just 25 percent of the snaps in Week 2 and can safely be left on waivers or benches for Week 3, despite the plus matchup against the Pittsburgh Steelers.

Surtain was excellent in Week 2, racking up nine solos, two assists, and one pass defended. As one of the best defenders in the league, Surtain will not always see this type of volume, but he remains a CB1/DB3 for IDP purposes. Treat him as such for a plus Week 3 matchup against the Los Angeles Chargers.
